Topological Dynamic Membrane Universe: The Particle Spectrum as an Inevitable Consequence of First Principles

Author Name   Jiangping Ma
Author Affiliation, Chongqing China

Abstract

The Topological Dynamic Membrane Universe (TDMU) hypothesis posits that our universe is a three-dimensional topological membrane embedded in a discrete combinatorial substrate, with matter emerging as topologically knotted vortex loops. This paper demonstrates how the particle spectrum arises inevitably from the interplay of microscopic dynamics, cosmic energy scale evolution, and collisional selection. We establish a recursive growth law for topological invariants, showing that the electron ($L=4$) and proton ($L=11933$) occupy positions on the same Fibonacci-type recursive tree. A universal "hard core + soft shell" structure is identified across all scales: particles possess a densely packed core providing stability, surrounded by a deformable outer layer of ancestral constituents. Crucially, we argue that the electron itself exhibits this layered structure—its core comprises four sub-elementary bricks arranged in a tetrahedral configuration, while its soft shell, composed of earlier-generation bricks, contributes negligibly to mass at current energy scales and thus remains unobserved. This framework offers a first-principles explanation for the electron-proton mass ratio, the origin of electric charge, and the relationship between nuclear fusion and high-energy cosmic evolution. Testable predictions, including resonance conditions in fusion cross-sections and potential substructure in precision electron measurements, are outlined.

Keywords Topological membrane · Recursive growth · Particle spectrum · Energy scale relativity · Chiral locking

1 Introduction

The Standard Model of particle physics, despite its empirical success, leaves fundamental questions unanswered: Why do particles possess the specific masses and charges they do? Are the electron, proton, and neutron merely accidental collections of more basic entities, or are they inevitable products of cosmic evolution? The Topological Dynamic Membrane Universe (TDMU) hypothesis offers a radical departure from conventional thinking by proposing that spacetime itself is a three-dimensional topological membrane embedded in a higher-dimensional combinatorial substrate [1]. Matter, in this picture, corresponds to stable topological knots—vortex loops knitted from the fabric of the membrane.

Recent advances in topological quantum computation have demonstrated that non-Abelian anyons, particularly Fibonacci anyons, exhibit fusion rules that naturally generate recursive structures [2, 3]. The Fibonacci anyon fusion rule $[1] \times [1] = [0] \oplus [1]$ provides the simplest possible model of non-Abelian statistics and has been extensively studied in the context of fractional quantum Hall systems [4, 5]. This mathematical framework resonates deeply with the recursive growth laws we observe in the TDMU particle spectrum.

This paper synthesizes and extends previous work, demonstrating how the particle spectrum emerges inevitably from first principles. We show that the recursive growth of topological structures, combined with an energy-dependent natural selection mechanism during the universe's cooling history, yields a discrete spectrum dominated by two long-lived species: the electron and the proton. Furthermore, we reveal a universal architectural principle: all stable particles, regardless of scale, exhibit a "hard core + soft shell" design optimized for survival in a high-energy collisional environment. This perspective leads to a profound corollary—the electron itself must possess an internal structure mirroring that of the proton, with its soft shell remaining invisible only due to the limitations of current observational energy scales.

The paper is organized as follows. Section 2 introduces the foundational concepts of bricks and topological charge, deriving the recursive growth law that governs particle complexity. Section 3 details the universal layered structure and the role of chiral locking in determining electric charge. Section 4 presents the cosmic selection mechanism that filters intermediate states. Section 5 addresses the binding energy correction that reconciles brick-count ratios with observed mass ratios. Section 6 extends the framework to nuclear fusion as a higher-order recursive process. Section 7 delves into the profound implications for electron structure. Section 8 outlines testable predictions, and Section 9 concludes with the unified picture.

